&gt;&gt; Thank you, Mark.

00:19:11.516 --> 00:19:13.756 A:middle
In this next section, let's talk

00:19:13.756 --> 00:19:15.596 A:middle
about privacy updates to

00:19:15.596 --> 00:19:16.626 A:middle
existing APIs.

00:19:18.376 --> 00:19:19.956 A:middle
We go through a series of five

00:19:20.146 --> 00:19:22.086 A:middle
updates in rapid fashion.

00:19:22.686 --> 00:19:25.916 A:middle
First, CNCopyCurrentNetworkInfo.

00:19:26.886 --> 00:19:29.126 A:middle
The CNCopyCurrentNetworkInfo API

00:19:29.676 --> 00:19:31.936 A:middle
returns the name and Mac address

00:19:32.236 --> 00:19:34.026 A:middle
of the Wi-Fi access point a

00:19:34.026 --> 00:19:35.996 A:middle
device is currently connected

00:19:36.046 --> 00:19:36.206 A:middle
to.

00:19:37.166 --> 00:19:40.176 A:middle
This affects privacy as a Wi-Fi

00:19:40.176 --> 00:19:42.616 A:middle
access point reveals a user's

00:19:42.616 --> 00:19:43.006 A:middle
location.

00:19:44.606 --> 00:19:48.056 A:middle
Starting in iOS 13, CNCopy will

00:19:48.056 --> 00:19:50.856 A:middle
only work for certain categories

00:19:50.856 --> 00:19:53.726 A:middle
of apps, apps that declared the

00:19:53.866 --> 00:19:57.196 A:middle
CNCopy entitlement and apps that

00:19:57.646 --> 00:20:00.006 A:middle
configured a virtual private

00:19:57.646 --> 00:20:00.006 A:middle
configured a virtual private

00:20:00.056 --> 00:20:00.436 A:middle
network.

00:20:01.206 --> 00:20:03.536 A:middle
Or apps that configured a Wi-Fi

00:20:03.536 --> 00:20:04.516 A:middle
network using the

00:20:04.516 --> 00:20:07.886 A:middle
NEHotspotConfiguration API or

00:20:07.886 --> 00:20:09.916 A:middle
apps that obtain location

00:20:09.916 --> 00:20:11.466 A:middle
permission from the user.

00:20:12.596 --> 00:20:14.016 A:middle
What this means for you is that

00:20:14.016 --> 00:20:15.876 A:middle
you may not be able to access

00:20:15.976 --> 00:20:17.266 A:middle
CNCopy anymore.

00:20:18.506 --> 00:20:20.036 A:middle
You can find out more details

00:20:20.156 --> 00:20:21.526 A:middle
about this in the networking

00:20:21.526 --> 00:20:22.726 A:middle
sessions listed below.

00:20:24.306 --> 00:20:26.626 A:middle
Second, contacts access.

00:20:27.306 --> 00:20:30.376 A:middle
Starting in iOS 13, apps that

00:20:30.376 --> 00:20:32.216 A:middle
have been authorized by a user

00:20:32.406 --> 00:20:34.546 A:middle
to access contacts will no

00:20:34.546 --> 00:20:36.706 A:middle
longer have access to the notes

00:20:36.706 --> 00:20:37.916 A:middle
field of a contact.

00:20:38.856 --> 00:20:40.966 A:middle
The notes field of a contact

00:20:41.226 --> 00:20:43.316 A:middle
potentially includes sensitive

00:20:43.316 --> 00:20:45.476 A:middle
details such as sneaky comments

00:20:45.536 --> 00:20:46.376 A:middle
about your boss.

00:20:47.316 --> 00:20:49.046 A:middle
Most apps do not need access to

00:20:49.046 --> 00:20:49.466 A:middle
this data.

00:20:50.156 --> 00:20:52.096 A:middle
If you believe you need access

00:20:52.186 --> 00:20:53.816 A:middle
to it, please file an

00:20:53.816 --> 00:20:55.216 A:middle
entitlement request at the

00:20:55.216 --> 00:20:56.306 A:middle
following URL.

00:20:57.096 --> 00:21:00.086 A:middle
Third, Custom URL Schemes.

00:20:57.096 --> 00:21:00.086 A:middle
Third, Custom URL Schemes.

00:21:00.926 --> 00:21:03.156 A:middle
Previously, if your app was

00:21:03.156 --> 00:21:05.556 A:middle
launched by a Custom URL Scheme,

00:21:06.176 --> 00:21:08.356 A:middle
you could identify the app that

00:21:08.356 --> 00:21:10.586 A:middle
launched you via an option of

00:21:10.626 --> 00:21:11.586 A:middle
open URL.

00:21:12.716 --> 00:21:14.556 A:middle
This revealed applications

00:21:14.646 --> 00:21:16.256 A:middle
installed on a user's device.

00:21:17.106 --> 00:21:20.016 A:middle
Starting in iOS 13, the source

00:21:20.016 --> 00:21:22.466 A:middle
application is only revealed to

00:21:22.466 --> 00:21:24.276 A:middle
apps from the same developer.

00:21:25.146 --> 00:21:27.446 A:middle
Fourth, Game Center.

00:21:28.426 --> 00:21:30.336 A:middle
In order to improve player

00:21:30.456 --> 00:21:33.696 A:middle
privacy, Game Center introduces

00:21:33.936 --> 00:21:36.656 A:middle
two new APIs.

00:21:36.706 --> 00:21:38.606 A:middle
The teamPlayerID for a

00:21:38.706 --> 00:21:40.626 A:middle
team-scoped player identifier

00:21:40.936 --> 00:21:42.336 A:middle
and the gamePlayerID for a

00:21:42.396 --> 00:21:44.266 A:middle
game-scoped player identifier.

00:21:45.096 --> 00:21:47.146 A:middle
The existing playerID identifier

00:21:47.516 --> 00:21:48.606 A:middle
is being deprecated.

00:21:49.656 --> 00:21:51.836 A:middle
This changes which identifier

00:21:52.136 --> 00:21:53.516 A:middle
you may use in your gaming app.

00:21:54.256 --> 00:21:56.096 A:middle
For more information, please

00:21:56.096 --> 00:21:57.746 A:middle
check out the Game Center video

00:21:57.946 --> 00:21:59.726 A:middle
in the WWDC app.

00:22:00.096 --> 00:22:01.986 A:middle
And five, contextual

00:22:02.046 --> 00:22:02.956 A:middle
information.

00:22:04.036 --> 00:22:06.586 A:middle
IOS doesn't know when your app

00:22:06.586 --> 00:22:08.616 A:middle
is most helpful to users.

00:22:09.656 --> 00:22:11.646 A:middle
You can provide contextual

00:22:11.646 --> 00:22:13.986 A:middle
information, entry point into

00:22:13.986 --> 00:22:17.546 A:middle
your app via two main APIs,

00:22:17.546 --> 00:22:19.966 A:middle
NSUserActivity, to promote your

00:22:20.186 --> 00:22:23.156 A:middle
app in Search results, and

00:22:23.226 --> 00:22:25.236 A:middle
SiriKit INInteraction to promote

00:22:25.236 --> 00:22:26.686 A:middle
your app on on-device

00:22:26.766 --> 00:22:28.456 A:middle
intelligent scenarios such as

00:22:28.726 --> 00:22:31.516 A:middle
Maps Shortcuts and new this year

00:22:31.516 --> 00:22:32.206 A:middle
in the Share Sheet.

00:22:32.866 --> 00:22:35.356 A:middle
If you do promote your app, be a

00:22:35.356 --> 00:22:35.916 A:middle
good sport.

00:22:36.676 --> 00:22:38.336 A:middle
Delete content that was removed

00:22:38.336 --> 00:22:38.826 A:middle
from your app.

00:22:39.906 --> 00:22:41.606 A:middle
You don't want Siri Shortcuts to

00:22:41.606 --> 00:22:43.336 A:middle
make a suggestion to content

00:22:43.486 --> 00:22:44.676 A:middle
that does not exist anymore.

00:22:45.386 --> 00:22:47.246 A:middle
Simply call the corresponding

00:22:47.406 --> 00:22:49.516 A:middle
deletion APIs.

00:22:49.516 --> 00:22:50.616 A:middle
We just went through a series a

00:22:50.616 --> 00:22:53.146 A:middle
five privacy updates to existing

00:22:53.146 --> 00:22:53.426 A:middle
APIs.

00:22:54.236 --> 00:22:56.436 A:middle
In our next section, we take a

00:22:56.436 --> 00:22:57.836 A:middle
step back.

00:22:58.156 --> 00:23:00.746 A:middle
We discuss how a privacy

00:22:58.156 --> 00:23:00.746 A:middle
We discuss how a privacy

00:23:00.786 --> 00:23:03.476 A:middle
challenge can be a chance to

00:23:03.626 --> 00:23:04.066 A:middle
innovate.

00:23:05.036 --> 00:23:07.226 A:middle
Privacy is fundamental to the

00:23:07.226 --> 00:23:08.766 A:middle
design of every product.

00:23:09.186 --> 00:23:11.126 A:middle
At Apple, in the Privacy Team,

00:23:11.356 --> 00:23:12.866 A:middle
we work with engineers all

00:23:12.866 --> 00:23:15.266 A:middle
across Apple to build privacy

00:23:15.266 --> 00:23:16.336 A:middle
into our products.

00:23:17.926 --> 00:23:20.666 A:middle
Once in a while, we hit a very

00:23:20.666 --> 00:23:23.546 A:middle
hard problem, a feature that we

00:23:23.546 --> 00:23:25.406 A:middle
really want to ship, but it's

00:23:25.406 --> 00:23:27.276 A:middle
not obvious how to protect

00:23:27.556 --> 00:23:28.076 A:middle
privacy.

00:23:29.636 --> 00:23:31.676 A:middle
So when that happens, we decide

00:23:31.676 --> 00:23:32.836 A:middle
to challenge ourselves.

00:23:33.236 --> 00:23:35.006 A:middle
We aim to build a great feature

00:23:35.226 --> 00:23:36.756 A:middle
without giving away user

00:23:36.756 --> 00:23:38.926 A:middle
information, so we lean on our

00:23:38.926 --> 00:23:41.646 A:middle
privacy principles to find

00:23:41.646 --> 00:23:43.406 A:middle
solutions and innovate.

00:23:44.686 --> 00:23:46.786 A:middle
Today, we want to inspire you to

00:23:46.786 --> 00:23:47.306 A:middle
do the same.

00:23:48.286 --> 00:23:49.686 A:middle
Let's look at three critical

00:23:49.686 --> 00:23:51.346 A:middle
areas of the user experience,

00:23:52.016 --> 00:23:54.676 A:middle
Machine Learning, Find My, and

00:23:54.676 --> 00:23:54.896 A:middle
Home.

00:23:56.026 --> 00:23:57.366 A:middle
Let's start with Machine

00:23:57.366 --> 00:23:57.616 A:middle
Learning.

00:23:58.436 --> 00:24:00.196 A:middle
There are many ways to build

00:23:58.436 --> 00:24:00.196 A:middle
There are many ways to build

00:24:00.406 --> 00:24:01.726 A:middle
Machine Learning applications.

00:24:02.446 --> 00:24:04.656 A:middle
Usually we need to train a model

00:24:05.096 --> 00:24:06.326 A:middle
and then evaluate it.

00:24:06.986 --> 00:24:09.006 A:middle
So the first privacy challenge

00:24:09.246 --> 00:24:11.436 A:middle
with Machine Learning is how to

00:24:11.436 --> 00:24:13.536 A:middle
train a machine learning model

00:24:14.216 --> 00:24:16.086 A:middle
but without collecting sensitive

00:24:16.216 --> 00:24:18.886 A:middle
user data while personalizing

00:24:18.886 --> 00:24:21.396 A:middle
the model to every user and

00:24:22.076 --> 00:24:24.066 A:middle
significantly improving the user

00:24:24.066 --> 00:24:24.516 A:middle
experience.

00:24:25.186 --> 00:24:27.106 A:middle
And again, it usually starts

00:24:27.176 --> 00:24:29.606 A:middle
with data, and it's usually a

00:24:29.606 --> 00:24:30.616 A:middle
lot of data.

00:24:31.946 --> 00:24:33.326 A:middle
And it can be challenging to

00:24:33.326 --> 00:24:33.866 A:middle
find data.

00:24:33.866 --> 00:24:35.686 A:middle
There are multiple options.

00:24:36.456 --> 00:24:38.556 A:middle
The first option is to collect

00:24:38.556 --> 00:24:39.426 A:middle
data from users.

00:24:40.406 --> 00:24:42.686 A:middle
So to protect user privacy, it's

00:24:42.686 --> 00:24:44.796 A:middle
important to apply best privacy

00:24:44.906 --> 00:24:46.956 A:middle
practices such as randomizing

00:24:46.956 --> 00:24:48.826 A:middle
identifiers, rounding or

00:24:48.826 --> 00:24:49.456 A:middle
sampling.

00:24:50.416 --> 00:24:53.466 A:middle
But sometimes data is inherently

00:24:53.586 --> 00:24:55.866 A:middle
sensitive, like the picture of

00:24:55.866 --> 00:24:56.626 A:middle
user's face.

00:24:56.886 --> 00:24:59.286 A:middle
A second option is to run a user

00:24:59.286 --> 00:24:59.656 A:middle
study.

00:25:01.116 --> 00:25:03.826 A:middle
We invite select users to test

00:25:03.826 --> 00:25:05.606 A:middle
or feature in private and

00:25:05.606 --> 00:25:06.546 A:middle
collect their data.

00:25:07.516 --> 00:25:09.456 A:middle
We did this ourselves to train

00:25:09.656 --> 00:25:10.226 A:middle
Face ID.

00:25:11.306 --> 00:25:13.286 A:middle
Finally, their external

00:25:13.286 --> 00:25:13.956 A:middle
datasets.

00:25:14.786 --> 00:25:16.286 A:middle
Some are publicly available for

00:25:16.286 --> 00:25:17.246 A:middle
research purposes.

00:25:17.746 --> 00:25:19.416 A:middle
Others require careful

00:25:19.446 --> 00:25:21.186 A:middle
collaboration with other

00:25:21.186 --> 00:25:23.766 A:middle
companies and raise their own

00:25:23.976 --> 00:25:24.896 A:middle
privacy challenges.

00:25:26.046 --> 00:25:28.696 A:middle
Once you have data, you can

00:25:28.696 --> 00:25:29.306 A:middle
train a model.

00:25:30.316 --> 00:25:32.186 A:middle
You can, for example, use Create

00:25:32.186 --> 00:25:32.306 A:middle
ML.

00:25:33.066 --> 00:25:35.416 A:middle
A train model is great for most

00:25:35.416 --> 00:25:37.926 A:middle
users, but users are different,

00:25:38.736 --> 00:25:39.976 A:middle
each with their own needs.

00:25:41.186 --> 00:25:43.166 A:middle
What if you needed to tailor, to

00:25:43.286 --> 00:25:45.546 A:middle
personalize a model to specific

00:25:45.816 --> 00:25:46.336 A:middle
users?

00:25:47.416 --> 00:25:49.086 A:middle
This year, we introduce

00:25:49.086 --> 00:25:51.316 A:middle
updatable Core ML models.

00:25:51.836 --> 00:25:53.876 A:middle
Send your updatable model to the

00:25:53.876 --> 00:25:54.236 A:middle
device.

00:25:55.116 --> 00:25:57.316 A:middle
An updatable model takes in

00:25:57.316 --> 00:25:59.126 A:middle
training data from the user and

00:25:59.126 --> 00:26:01.296 A:middle
produces a new personalized

00:25:59.126 --> 00:26:01.296 A:middle
produces a new personalized

00:26:01.626 --> 00:26:01.936 A:middle
model.

00:26:02.826 --> 00:26:04.376 A:middle
We do this ourselves with Face

00:26:04.406 --> 00:26:04.786 A:middle
ID.

00:26:05.276 --> 00:26:07.436 A:middle
Face ID automatically adjusts to

00:26:07.436 --> 00:26:08.006 A:middle
your appearance.

00:26:08.806 --> 00:26:10.906 A:middle
If you grow a beard or grow

00:26:10.906 --> 00:26:13.146 A:middle
longer hair, Face ID still

00:26:13.146 --> 00:26:13.876 A:middle
recognizes you.

00:26:14.026 --> 00:26:15.876 A:middle
And this all happens on the

00:26:15.876 --> 00:26:16.146 A:middle
device.

00:26:17.746 --> 00:26:19.976 A:middle
Training uses resources though,

00:26:20.526 --> 00:26:22.656 A:middle
and it may affect a user

00:26:23.326 --> 00:26:24.056 A:middle
experience.

00:26:24.206 --> 00:26:25.366 A:middle
While there's a new Background

00:26:25.366 --> 00:26:27.606 A:middle
Task API that allows you to

00:26:27.606 --> 00:26:29.536 A:middle
schedule machine learning tasks

00:26:29.886 --> 00:26:32.406 A:middle
in the background, we recommend

00:26:32.856 --> 00:26:34.746 A:middle
scheduling a task within a week

00:26:34.746 --> 00:26:35.096 A:middle
or less.

00:26:36.356 --> 00:26:38.526 A:middle
If you choose a date too far

00:26:38.526 --> 00:26:40.876 A:middle
into the future, iOS may not

00:26:40.916 --> 00:26:42.266 A:middle
schedule it.

00:26:42.586 --> 00:26:43.706 A:middle
You can learn more about the

00:26:43.706 --> 00:26:45.276 A:middle
Background Task API in our

00:26:45.276 --> 00:26:45.906 A:middle
session below.

00:26:46.686 --> 00:26:50.126 A:middle
But sometimes, we need more than

00:26:50.126 --> 00:26:51.016 A:middle
one user's data.

00:26:51.896 --> 00:26:54.026 A:middle
We need data from many different

00:26:54.026 --> 00:26:54.586 A:middle
users.

00:26:55.576 --> 00:26:57.676 A:middle
Today, I want to share with you

00:26:58.676 --> 00:27:00.296 A:middle
a new technique that we are

00:26:58.676 --> 00:27:00.296 A:middle
a new technique that we are

00:27:00.296 --> 00:27:00.876 A:middle
developing.

00:27:02.066 --> 00:27:03.726 A:middle
This is an example of how we

00:27:03.726 --> 00:27:06.386 A:middle
innovate in privacy for machine

00:27:06.386 --> 00:27:06.626 A:middle
learning.

00:27:07.656 --> 00:27:09.906 A:middle
Federated Learning is a new

00:27:09.906 --> 00:27:11.236 A:middle
approach that is picking up

00:27:11.236 --> 00:27:12.596 A:middle
steam in the machine learning

00:27:12.596 --> 00:27:13.096 A:middle
community.

00:27:13.736 --> 00:27:15.806 A:middle
Today, we're introducing Private

00:27:16.126 --> 00:27:18.136 A:middle
Federated Learning by combining

00:27:18.316 --> 00:27:19.816 A:middle
Federated Learning with

00:27:19.816 --> 00:27:21.016 A:middle
differential privacy.

00:27:21.736 --> 00:27:25.406 A:middle
The idea is simple, instead of

00:27:25.446 --> 00:27:27.826 A:middle
collecting user data with

00:27:27.826 --> 00:27:30.066 A:middle
Private Federated Learning, we

00:27:30.066 --> 00:27:31.986 A:middle
collect model updates.

00:27:32.666 --> 00:27:35.636 A:middle
In other words, devices tell the

00:27:35.636 --> 00:27:38.006 A:middle
server how a machine learning

00:27:38.006 --> 00:27:40.166 A:middle
model should be updated.

00:27:41.236 --> 00:27:42.786 A:middle
Let's walk through an example.

00:27:43.726 --> 00:27:46.336 A:middle
It all starts with the server

00:27:46.436 --> 00:27:48.136 A:middle
giving devices an original

00:27:48.226 --> 00:27:48.556 A:middle
model.

00:27:49.476 --> 00:27:50.506 A:middle
We show it in white here.

00:27:51.326 --> 00:27:53.376 A:middle
Each device trains the model

00:27:53.446 --> 00:27:55.846 A:middle
under local data and obtains a

00:27:55.846 --> 00:27:56.326 A:middle
new model.

00:27:57.436 --> 00:27:58.976 A:middle
We show it here by changing the

00:27:58.976 --> 00:27:59.266 A:middle
color.

00:27:59.696 --> 00:28:00.986 A:middle
They compute the difference

00:27:59.696 --> 00:28:00.986 A:middle
They compute the difference

00:28:01.136 --> 00:28:02.996 A:middle
between this new model and the

00:28:02.996 --> 00:28:04.836 A:middle
original one and send these

00:28:04.836 --> 00:28:06.846 A:middle
model updates back to Apple

00:28:06.846 --> 00:28:07.396 A:middle
servers.

00:28:09.466 --> 00:28:11.076 A:middle
The server aggregates these

00:28:11.076 --> 00:28:13.046 A:middle
model updates into a new

00:28:13.046 --> 00:28:15.216 A:middle
enhanced machine learning model

00:28:15.626 --> 00:28:16.506 A:middle
that we show here with a

00:28:16.506 --> 00:28:17.336 A:middle
gradient color.

00:28:18.466 --> 00:28:20.826 A:middle
Note that in this process no

00:28:20.826 --> 00:28:23.276 A:middle
user data is sent in plain, and

00:28:23.276 --> 00:28:24.856 A:middle
we have no needs for any user or

00:28:24.856 --> 00:28:26.056 A:middle
device identifiers.

00:28:27.356 --> 00:28:28.976 A:middle
The server then updates the

00:28:28.976 --> 00:28:30.686 A:middle
devices back with a new model,

00:28:31.266 --> 00:28:33.386 A:middle
and this cycle can go back and

00:28:33.466 --> 00:28:35.256 A:middle
forth between the devices and

00:28:35.256 --> 00:28:35.656 A:middle
the server.

00:28:36.416 --> 00:28:38.646 A:middle
From a privacy perspective, we

00:28:38.646 --> 00:28:40.206 A:middle
need to analyze whether those

00:28:40.206 --> 00:28:42.686 A:middle
model updates include sensitive

00:28:42.916 --> 00:28:43.176 A:middle
data.

00:28:44.106 --> 00:28:46.056 A:middle
It's often considered that model

00:28:46.056 --> 00:28:46.986 A:middle
updates are fine.

00:28:47.216 --> 00:28:48.566 A:middle
They're not plain user data.

00:28:49.576 --> 00:28:52.016 A:middle
But unfortunately, in some

00:28:52.076 --> 00:28:54.846 A:middle
corner cases, a curious server

00:28:55.446 --> 00:28:57.866 A:middle
could attempt to reconstruct the

00:28:57.866 --> 00:28:59.806 A:middle
user data from model updates.

00:29:00.526 --> 00:29:02.686 A:middle
For example, here, if a user

00:29:02.686 --> 00:29:04.766 A:middle
sent model updates relative to

00:29:04.766 --> 00:29:07.446 A:middle
this castle, a curious server

00:29:07.446 --> 00:29:09.926 A:middle
may be able to reconstruct the

00:29:09.986 --> 00:29:11.776 A:middle
castle image from the model

00:29:11.776 --> 00:29:12.046 A:middle
update.

00:29:12.736 --> 00:29:15.136 A:middle
So, to prevent this, we protect

00:29:15.376 --> 00:29:18.236 A:middle
model updates using on device

00:29:18.366 --> 00:29:20.356 A:middle
and on the server Separated

00:29:20.686 --> 00:29:23.026 A:middle
Differential Privacy and Central

00:29:23.506 --> 00:29:24.766 A:middle
Differential Privacy.

00:29:25.886 --> 00:29:28.246 A:middle
Differential Privacy adds noise

00:29:28.556 --> 00:29:29.546 A:middle
to the model updates.

00:29:30.186 --> 00:29:32.186 A:middle
This ensures that a curious

00:29:32.186 --> 00:29:35.086 A:middle
server cannot reconstruct the

00:29:35.086 --> 00:29:35.676 A:middle
image anymore.

00:29:36.496 --> 00:29:38.946 A:middle
You can find more details about

00:29:38.976 --> 00:29:40.586 A:middle
how we use Separated

00:29:40.586 --> 00:29:42.016 A:middle
Differential Privacy in the

00:29:42.086 --> 00:29:44.796 A:middle
paper below that we wrote.

00:29:45.066 --> 00:29:47.146 A:middle
Private Federated Learning can

00:29:47.146 --> 00:29:49.156 A:middle
be used to improve on-device

00:29:49.296 --> 00:29:49.966 A:middle
intelligence.

00:29:50.806 --> 00:29:52.246 A:middle
This is not a research

00:29:52.246 --> 00:29:52.796 A:middle
experiment.

00:29:53.536 --> 00:29:54.666 A:middle
We are starting to use this

00:29:54.696 --> 00:29:56.596 A:middle
technology in iOS 13 in a

00:29:56.596 --> 00:29:58.706 A:middle
variety of use cases including

00:29:58.706 --> 00:30:00.646 A:middle
QuickType keyboard, personalized

00:29:58.706 --> 00:30:00.646 A:middle
QuickType keyboard, personalized

00:30:00.646 --> 00:30:02.126 A:middle
Hey Siri, and more in the

00:30:02.176 --> 00:30:02.496 A:middle
future.

00:30:05.036 --> 00:30:07.266 A:middle
Once you train a model, you want

00:30:07.266 --> 00:30:07.666 A:middle
to use it.

00:30:08.346 --> 00:30:10.606 A:middle
This raises the second privacy

00:30:10.606 --> 00:30:11.986 A:middle
challenge with machine learning.

00:30:13.276 --> 00:30:15.616 A:middle
How to evaluate a model without

00:30:15.866 --> 00:30:18.156 A:middle
collecting user data in a fast

00:30:18.156 --> 00:30:20.166 A:middle
way and without suffering from

00:30:20.166 --> 00:30:21.406 A:middle
Internet connection delays.

00:30:21.406 --> 00:30:24.546 A:middle
The first way that comes to mind

00:30:24.856 --> 00:30:26.576 A:middle
is to simply send user data to

00:30:26.676 --> 00:30:28.166 A:middle
the server, evaluate the model

00:30:28.166 --> 00:30:29.376 A:middle
there, and get back the

00:30:29.376 --> 00:30:30.046 A:middle
inference.

00:30:30.866 --> 00:30:32.616 A:middle
But this means sending more user

00:30:32.616 --> 00:30:33.536 A:middle
data to the server.

00:30:33.876 --> 00:30:36.236 A:middle
Instead, we prefer on-device

00:30:36.236 --> 00:30:36.896 A:middle
intelligence.

00:30:37.406 --> 00:30:38.706 A:middle
We send a model down to the

00:30:38.706 --> 00:30:39.216 A:middle
device.

00:30:39.666 --> 00:30:41.286 A:middle
The device evaluates it locally.

00:30:42.166 --> 00:30:43.586 A:middle
This has a lot of advantages.

00:30:44.276 --> 00:30:45.376 A:middle
It's less data sent to the

00:30:45.446 --> 00:30:46.016 A:middle
servers.

00:30:46.546 --> 00:30:47.966 A:middle
It works even if you don't have

00:30:47.966 --> 00:30:49.696 A:middle
Internet, and it's fast if you

00:30:49.776 --> 00:30:51.186 A:middle
use Core ML.

00:30:51.496 --> 00:30:54.546 A:middle
Core ML is optimized to run fast

00:30:54.826 --> 00:30:56.986 A:middle
on iOS devices and others.

00:30:57.166 --> 00:30:59.246 A:middle
It's easy to convert your

00:30:59.246 --> 00:31:01.286 A:middle
existing model to a Core ML

00:30:59.246 --> 00:31:01.286 A:middle
existing model to a Core ML

00:31:01.466 --> 00:31:04.396 A:middle
model, and this year, we expand

00:31:04.566 --> 00:31:05.316 A:middle
the number of model

00:31:05.316 --> 00:31:07.046 A:middle
architectures that are

00:31:07.046 --> 00:31:07.686 A:middle
supported.

00:31:08.446 --> 00:31:09.886 A:middle
You can learn more in the Core

00:31:09.886 --> 00:31:13.016 A:middle
ML session listed below.

00:31:13.366 --> 00:31:15.496 A:middle
On-device intelligence provides

00:31:15.756 --> 00:31:19.506 A:middle
strong privacy advantages, and

00:31:19.506 --> 00:31:21.386 A:middle
we like to communicate those

00:31:21.386 --> 00:31:23.256 A:middle
advantages to our users in the

00:31:23.376 --> 00:31:25.986 A:middle
form of privacy assurances.

00:31:26.626 --> 00:31:29.376 A:middle
A privacy assurance is a simple

00:31:29.446 --> 00:31:31.696 A:middle
privacy sentence that we share

00:31:31.936 --> 00:31:32.696 A:middle
with our users.

00:31:33.336 --> 00:31:34.896 A:middle
This is not a privacy policy

00:31:34.896 --> 00:31:35.556 A:middle
with legalese.

00:31:36.116 --> 00:31:38.596 A:middle
For example, with Face ID, we

00:31:38.596 --> 00:31:41.726 A:middle
say, Face ID data never leaves

00:31:41.776 --> 00:31:42.296 A:middle
the device.

00:31:43.476 --> 00:31:44.816 A:middle
This is a clear and strong

00:31:44.816 --> 00:31:47.066 A:middle
statement about our approach to

00:31:47.066 --> 00:31:48.526 A:middle
privacy with Face ID.

00:31:48.926 --> 00:31:51.696 A:middle
It's easy for all users to

00:31:52.376 --> 00:31:53.036 A:middle
understand.

00:31:53.036 --> 00:31:54.916 A:middle
All right, this was machine

00:31:54.916 --> 00:31:55.246 A:middle
learning.

00:31:56.396 --> 00:31:59.206 A:middle
Let's talk about Find My next.

00:31:59.796 --> 00:32:01.396 A:middle
This year we announced a new

00:31:59.796 --> 00:32:01.396 A:middle
This year we announced a new

00:32:01.506 --> 00:32:03.426 A:middle
Find My application that merges

00:32:03.576 --> 00:32:05.806 A:middle
the Find My Friends and the Find

00:32:05.916 --> 00:32:07.706 A:middle
My iPhone apps.

00:32:07.796 --> 00:32:09.666 A:middle
One feature that we were very

00:32:09.666 --> 00:32:11.876 A:middle
excited about is the offline

00:32:11.876 --> 00:32:12.696 A:middle
finding feature.

00:32:13.476 --> 00:32:14.936 A:middle
Here's a challenge that was

00:32:14.936 --> 00:32:16.096 A:middle
brought to our attention.

00:32:16.696 --> 00:32:19.636 A:middle
A user forgot their MacBook at

00:32:19.636 --> 00:32:20.476 A:middle
the public library.

00:32:21.896 --> 00:32:24.176 A:middle
The user realizes that, launches

00:32:24.176 --> 00:32:26.036 A:middle
the new Find My app and attempts

00:32:26.036 --> 00:32:28.756 A:middle
to find the MacBook, but it may

00:32:28.756 --> 00:32:30.726 A:middle
not work because the MacBook is

00:32:30.726 --> 00:32:33.736 A:middle
not connected to the Internet.

00:32:33.736 --> 00:32:35.186 A:middle
So the privacy challenge is

00:32:35.956 --> 00:32:38.356 A:middle
support finding devices between

00:32:38.356 --> 00:32:41.266 A:middle
Mac and iPhone or a Watch that

00:32:41.266 --> 00:32:43.316 A:middle
is, even when it's not connected

00:32:43.526 --> 00:32:44.656 A:middle
to the Internet when it's

00:32:44.696 --> 00:32:47.266 A:middle
offline while protecting the

00:32:47.296 --> 00:32:50.256 A:middle
privacy of the lost devices but

00:32:50.256 --> 00:32:52.266 A:middle
also of anyone that would help

00:32:52.266 --> 00:32:54.166 A:middle
you find those lost devices and

00:32:54.166 --> 00:32:56.106 A:middle
making sure that Apple doesn't

00:32:56.106 --> 00:32:58.166 A:middle
learn anything in the process.

00:32:59.126 --> 00:33:01.036 A:middle
And, of course, with limited

00:32:59.126 --> 00:33:01.036 A:middle
And, of course, with limited

00:33:01.036 --> 00:33:02.066 A:middle
impact on the battery life.

00:33:02.986 --> 00:33:04.056 A:middle
This was a long list of

00:33:04.056 --> 00:33:05.936 A:middle
challenges, and so the idea for

00:33:05.936 --> 00:33:07.336 A:middle
us was to rely on crowd

00:33:07.336 --> 00:33:07.846 A:middle
sourcing.

00:33:08.756 --> 00:33:10.846 A:middle
We wanted to make it easy to

00:33:10.846 --> 00:33:12.826 A:middle
detect a lost MacBook via

00:33:12.826 --> 00:33:14.746 A:middle
Bluetooth and report its

00:33:14.746 --> 00:33:16.096 A:middle
location to Apple servers.

00:33:16.746 --> 00:33:18.706 A:middle
But we couldn't rely on a static

00:33:18.706 --> 00:33:20.126 A:middle
identifier broadcast over

00:33:20.126 --> 00:33:20.536 A:middle
Bluetooth.

00:33:21.226 --> 00:33:23.276 A:middle
A static identifier could allow

00:33:23.626 --> 00:33:25.856 A:middle
anyone to track any device at

00:33:25.856 --> 00:33:27.856 A:middle
any time, and we couldn't do

00:33:28.976 --> 00:33:29.106 A:middle
that.

00:33:29.336 --> 00:33:32.426 A:middle
Instead, the MacBook broadcasts

00:33:32.756 --> 00:33:35.146 A:middle
and ephemeral public encryption

00:33:35.146 --> 00:33:35.316 A:middle
key.

00:33:36.526 --> 00:33:39.106 A:middle
This key changes over time.

00:33:40.106 --> 00:33:43.036 A:middle
Any nearby phone can receive

00:33:43.036 --> 00:33:44.646 A:middle
over Bluetooth this encryption

00:33:44.646 --> 00:33:46.796 A:middle
key, compute their own location,

00:33:47.056 --> 00:33:48.446 A:middle
and encrypt it with the

00:33:48.446 --> 00:33:49.126 A:middle
encryption key.

00:33:50.326 --> 00:33:52.116 A:middle
Then, this encrypted data can be

00:33:52.116 --> 00:33:53.626 A:middle
submitted to Apple servers.

00:33:54.476 --> 00:33:56.766 A:middle
Note here that since location is

00:33:56.766 --> 00:33:59.356 A:middle
encrypted, Apple cannot see it.

00:33:59.556 --> 00:34:01.266 A:middle
Also, note that no information

00:33:59.556 --> 00:34:01.266 A:middle
Also, note that no information

00:34:01.266 --> 00:34:02.506 A:middle
is provided about the nearby

00:34:02.506 --> 00:34:04.036 A:middle
phone that helped find the lost

00:34:04.036 --> 00:34:04.506 A:middle
device.

00:34:05.186 --> 00:34:07.916 A:middle
Finally, the owner can ask Apple

00:34:07.916 --> 00:34:09.716 A:middle
later on for the corresponding

00:34:09.716 --> 00:34:11.996 A:middle
encrypted data, decrypt it to

00:34:11.996 --> 00:34:14.085 A:middle
obtain the location to its lost

00:34:14.166 --> 00:34:14.716 A:middle
device.

00:34:15.505 --> 00:34:17.666 A:middle
With this proposal, we can share

00:34:17.926 --> 00:34:19.806 A:middle
the following privacy assurance

00:34:20.016 --> 00:34:20.766 A:middle
with our users.

00:34:21.735 --> 00:34:24.565 A:middle
Apple does not know the location

00:34:24.565 --> 00:34:26.775 A:middle
of any offline devices or

00:34:26.775 --> 00:34:27.576 A:middle
finders.

00:34:28.426 --> 00:34:29.706 A:middle
This is a big result.

00:34:30.085 --> 00:34:31.706 A:middle
We found a way to design a

00:34:31.706 --> 00:34:34.186 A:middle
fantastic feature with industry

00:34:34.295 --> 00:34:35.446 A:middle
leading privacy.

00:34:36.045 --> 00:34:41.156 A:middle
Next, let's talk about the Home.

00:34:42.315 --> 00:34:44.616 A:middle
The Home is a safe place, and

00:34:44.616 --> 00:34:45.976 A:middle
important place for all of us.

00:34:46.656 --> 00:34:48.416 A:middle
It's a safe place we go to after

00:34:48.416 --> 00:34:50.085 A:middle
work or after a long day at

00:34:50.085 --> 00:34:52.856 A:middle
WWDC, and as the popularity of

00:34:52.926 --> 00:34:55.746 A:middle
Smart homes increases, so does

00:34:56.045 --> 00:34:57.836 A:middle
new privacy threats emerge.

00:34:58.796 --> 00:35:00.846 A:middle
Many customers have concerns

00:34:58.796 --> 00:35:00.846 A:middle
Many customers have concerns

00:35:00.996 --> 00:35:02.526 A:middle
about Smart home accessories,

00:35:02.906 --> 00:35:04.996 A:middle
and nothing is more sensitive

00:35:05.406 --> 00:35:07.456 A:middle
than security cameras in the

00:35:07.456 --> 00:35:07.656 A:middle
home.

00:35:08.786 --> 00:35:10.446 A:middle
So the privacy challenge here is

00:35:10.706 --> 00:35:12.856 A:middle
allowing users to view their

00:35:12.856 --> 00:35:15.356 A:middle
security cameras from anywhere

00:35:16.146 --> 00:35:18.216 A:middle
while allowing no one else to

00:35:18.216 --> 00:35:20.696 A:middle
access the video feed, not even

00:35:20.766 --> 00:35:23.416 A:middle
Apple, and still enabling Smart

00:35:23.746 --> 00:35:25.006 A:middle
camera experiences.

00:35:26.086 --> 00:35:27.266 A:middle
So we worked with camera

00:35:27.266 --> 00:35:29.206 A:middle
providers on two main things.

00:35:29.676 --> 00:35:32.466 A:middle
First, we rely on on-device

00:35:32.546 --> 00:35:34.366 A:middle
intelligence to do computer

00:35:34.366 --> 00:35:36.636 A:middle
vision in the home on the home

00:35:36.856 --> 00:35:38.206 A:middle
resident device.

00:35:38.936 --> 00:35:41.596 A:middle
Be it a HomePod, an Apple TV, or

00:35:41.596 --> 00:35:44.576 A:middle
an iPad, we detect people and

00:35:44.726 --> 00:35:46.736 A:middle
objects directly in the home,

00:35:47.356 --> 00:35:48.296 A:middle
not in the Cloud.

00:35:49.456 --> 00:35:51.596 A:middle
Second, we store camera

00:35:51.596 --> 00:35:53.256 A:middle
recordings in an end-to-end

00:35:53.256 --> 00:35:54.046 A:middle
encrypted manner.

00:35:55.196 --> 00:35:57.776 A:middle
This means only you can see the

00:35:57.816 --> 00:36:00.276 A:middle
content from your camera, and we

00:35:57.816 --> 00:36:00.276 A:middle
content from your camera, and we

00:36:00.276 --> 00:36:01.626 A:middle
can make the following privacy

00:36:01.626 --> 00:36:02.176 A:middle
assurance.

00:36:03.076 --> 00:36:05.536 A:middle
Only you can see the video from

00:36:05.536 --> 00:36:06.236 A:middle
your camera.

00:36:07.056 --> 00:36:08.306 A:middle
Short and sweet.

00:36:09.206 --> 00:36:11.016 A:middle
It's time to wrap up the privacy

00:36:11.016 --> 00:36:11.426 A:middle
session.

00:36:12.126 --> 00:36:13.766 A:middle
We talked about three privacy

00:36:13.766 --> 00:36:15.626 A:middle
challenges and showed you how we

00:36:15.626 --> 00:36:16.176 A:middle
solved them.

00:36:16.866 --> 00:36:18.886 A:middle
Throughout this presentation, we

00:36:18.886 --> 00:36:21.166 A:middle
also talked about API updates

00:36:21.166 --> 00:36:22.456 A:middle
and new features that we

00:36:22.456 --> 00:36:25.416 A:middle
designed with privacy.

00:36:25.416 --> 00:36:28.146 A:middle
Every year, every release, with

00:36:28.146 --> 00:36:30.776 A:middle
every product we challenge

00:36:30.776 --> 00:36:32.786 A:middle
ourselves to build great

00:36:32.886 --> 00:36:35.216 A:middle
features without giving away

00:36:35.466 --> 00:36:36.216 A:middle
user information.

00:36:37.266 --> 00:36:39.326 A:middle
Because privacy is fundamental

00:36:39.326 --> 00:36:40.996 A:middle
to the design of every product,

00:36:41.776 --> 00:36:44.296 A:middle
we share privacy assurances with

00:36:44.296 --> 00:36:44.846 A:middle
our users.

00:36:45.786 --> 00:36:48.376 A:middle
Simple sentences about our

00:36:48.376 --> 00:36:50.626 A:middle
commitment to protect user

00:36:50.626 --> 00:36:51.106 A:middle
privacy.

00:36:52.566 --> 00:36:54.186 A:middle
There are three things we want

00:36:54.186 --> 00:36:55.626 A:middle
you to remember today.

00:36:56.166 --> 00:36:59.316 A:middle
First, among the first questions

00:36:59.536 --> 00:37:01.056 A:middle
you should ask yourselves when

00:36:59.536 --> 00:37:01.056 A:middle
you should ask yourselves when

00:37:01.056 --> 00:37:02.996 A:middle
working on a new project is how

00:37:02.996 --> 00:37:05.086 A:middle
you will protect user data.

00:37:05.546 --> 00:37:08.546 A:middle
Ask what you should do, not what

00:37:08.546 --> 00:37:11.026 A:middle
you can do with your app.

00:37:11.386 --> 00:37:13.996 A:middle
Earn the trust of your users by

00:37:13.996 --> 00:37:16.266 A:middle
making it easy for them to know

00:37:16.266 --> 00:37:18.126 A:middle
that their privacy is protected

00:37:18.176 --> 00:37:20.006 A:middle
in your app.

00:37:20.456 --> 00:37:22.846 A:middle
Second, if you face a tough

00:37:22.916 --> 00:37:25.106 A:middle
privacy problem, challenge

00:37:25.106 --> 00:37:26.776 A:middle
yourself to find a solution.

00:37:28.106 --> 00:37:30.766 A:middle
Privacy is a chance to innovate.

00:37:31.566 --> 00:37:33.316 A:middle
Find a way to deliver your

00:37:33.396 --> 00:37:36.106 A:middle
feature without giving away more

00:37:36.106 --> 00:37:36.666 A:middle
user data.

00:37:38.176 --> 00:37:40.496 A:middle
And third, privacy is an

00:37:40.496 --> 00:37:42.896 A:middle
opportunity to engage with your

00:37:42.896 --> 00:37:43.436 A:middle
users.

00:37:44.936 --> 00:37:47.206 A:middle
Privacy is about people.

00:37:48.496 --> 00:37:51.156 A:middle
Don't let a privacy policy take

00:37:51.156 --> 00:37:51.946 A:middle
that away from you.

00:37:52.656 --> 00:37:54.416 A:middle
Share your privacy assurances

00:37:54.776 --> 00:37:55.706 A:middle
with your users.

00:37:56.716 --> 00:37:58.246 A:middle
If you have any more questions,

00:37:58.536 --> 00:38:00.106 A:middle
please join us in the privacy

00:37:58.536 --> 00:38:00.106 A:middle
please join us in the privacy

00:38:00.106 --> 00:38:01.676 A:middle
lab right after this talk.

